WEBVTT

00:09.609 --> 00:11.111
Oh, hello, Dad. Hi, Niles.

00:11.111 --> 00:12.612
May I get my usual, please?

00:12.612 --> 00:14.603
Niles, we're playing
squash in 20 minutes.

00:15.115 --> 00:16.104
Where are your togs?

00:16.616 --> 00:18.118
Oh, yes, I had to hide
them in my briefcase.

00:18.118 --> 00:19.619
I told Daphne I was
seeing patients all day.

00:19.619 --> 00:21.121
It was the only way I could get out

00:21.121 --> 00:22.110
of driving her to this flower show.

00:22.622 --> 00:23.623
It's two hours there and back.

00:23.623 --> 00:25.125
I see; well, we could have rescheduled.

00:25.125 --> 00:26.615
Did you really have to lie?

00:27.127 --> 00:28.617
Did I mention we'd be
joined by Daphne's mother,

00:29.129 --> 00:30.630
who's suffering from
some female complaint

00:30.630 --> 00:32.131
and can't get it through her head

00:32.131 --> 00:33.531
that I'm not a gynecologist?

00:33.767 --> 00:38.071
Ah. Well, then, you
had to save yourself.

00:38.071 --> 00:40.440
so, please, don't tell anyone
we're playing squash today.

00:40.440 --> 00:42.442
I can't have it getting back to Daphne.

00:42.442 --> 00:43.443
Right. Hey, guys.

00:43.443 --> 00:44.432
I'm so glad you're here.

00:45.145 --> 00:46.146
You can meet my new boyfriend.

00:46.146 --> 00:47.447
He's the hottest guy
I've dated since.. .

00:47.447 --> 00:48.448
Frasier.

00:48.448 --> 00:50.439
Okay, the hottest guy

00:51.151 --> 00:53.453
(cracking up) ; since Frasier.

00:53.453 --> 00:55.155
That's Alistair Burke.

00:55.155 --> 00:56.144
I know!

00:56.322 --> 00:58.258
Who's Alistair Burke?

00:58.258 --> 00:59.247
He is only the head of
the seattle Opera Guild

00:59.559 --> 01:01.261
and one of the finest
directors in the world.

01:01.261 --> 01:02.562
His productions are brilliant.

01:02.562 --> 01:04.263
He staged a Philip
Glass opera last year,

01:04.263 --> 01:05.561
and no one left.

01:06.266 --> 01:07.563
Alistair, uh, it's, it's Frasier Crane.

01:08.268 --> 01:09.569
Uh, we met last year
at the fund-raiser.

01:09.569 --> 01:10.570
Of course.

01:10.570 --> 01:12.272
You're on the radio.

01:12.272 --> 01:12.567
Yes, yes.

01:13.273 --> 01:14.262
And you're... don't tell me.

01:15.575 --> 01:18.178
All right, tell me.

01:18.178 --> 01:20.146
Niles Crane.

01:20.146 --> 01:22.215
Yes, we've both got
ticket s to your premiere,

01:22.215 --> 01:23.216
and, oh, we can't wait to see

01:23.216 --> 01:24.517
what magic you'll work with La Boheme.

01:24.517 --> 01:26.519
Well, I would be content

01:26.519 --> 01:29.522
if my Mimi would just
lay off the cheeseburgers.

01:29.522 --> 01:31.524
I sat her down yesterday and I said,

01:31.524 --> 01:33.526
'You're dying of consumption, dear,

01:33.526 --> 01:35.221
not overcon sumption. "

01:35.528 --> 01:36.517
(both guffawing)

01:37.230 --> 01:39.232
FRAsIER; Oh, that's hilarious!

01:39.232 --> 01:40.233
